    <p>
        <m>\textbf{Key Takeaway}</m>
    </p>
    <definition xml:id="def-velocity">
        <statement>
            <p>
                Velocity is refered to as distance covered in a specific direction per unit time. 
                It is a <term>vector quantity</term>, meaning it has both magnitude and direction.
            </p>
        </statement>
    </definition>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
                A car travels <m>100</m> meters to the east in <m>20</m> seconds. What is its velocity in m/s?
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                Velocity = <m>\frac{\text{Total Distance Covered in a Specified Direction}}{\text{Total Time Taken}}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>  \frac{100 \text{ m}}{20 \text{ s}} = 5 \text{ m/s}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example>
        <statement>
            <p>
               A Spacecraft travels <m>300</m> kilometers to the north in <m>5</m> minutes. Calculate its velocity in km/h.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            <p>
                First, convert the time from minutes to hours: <m>5 \text{ minutes} = \frac{5}{60} \text{ hours} = \frac{1}{12} \text{ hours}</m>.
            </p>
            <p>
                Velocity = <m>\frac{\text{Total Distance Covered in a Specified Direction}}{\text{Total Time Taken}}</m>
            </p>
            <p>
                <m>  \frac{300 \text{ km}}{\frac{1}{12} \text{ hours}} = 300 \text{ km} \times \frac{12}{1} = 3600 \text{ km/h}</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
    </example>

